## Introduction

Why do people donate money?  When presented with the theme of “sustainable environments"  for this quarter’s CS 188 Human-Computer Interaction course at the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA), our team interpreted the prompt in a broad sense. Initial brainstorming sessions yielded various ideas ranging from the impacts of sustainability to personal productivity. For example, one initial concept we had was a time management mobile application centered around mental health. While iterating on the concept, we ultimately realized we wanted to design a system that not only served the user, but better matched with the sustainable environment theme of the quarter.  One of the approaches to sustainable environments that we wanted to address was “social sustainability”.  Specifically, how could we get people to sustainably take actions that they believe they should be taking?  Charitable giving became one of the approaches to “social sustainability” that we considered. This new direction was sparked by our team member Matthew, an active leader in the Effective Altruism student organization at UCLA, who identified a critical gap in the non-profit sector:  most people think they **should** donate money to charity, but almost no one does **consistently**.  

Motivated by this insight, we examined the current landscape of digital philanthropy and found it lacking in flexibility. The actual user experience of donating is often cumbersome, intimidating, and not rewarding.  Most charity platforms force users into a binary choice of either donating substantially at once, or subscribing to monthly donations. While these choices may be effective for established donors with strong financial flexibility, they are often highly frictional to people who may not necessarily have the means to donate in large amounts frequently. In particular, existing charitable giving structures alienate students and young professionals who wish to contribute and support causes through charities, but lack the financial security or confidence to commit to large sums frequently. 

To bridge this gap, we developed **Aspiration**, a cross-platform web application and Chrome extension.  Aspiration strives to make donating easier and less burdensome by utilizing a “round-up” mechanism, automatically rounding online purchases to the nearest dollar and donating the difference in a transparent way. By integrating charitable acts into everyday spending, Aspiration transforms sporadic, burdensome donations into consistent, effortless micro-contributions, which empowers users to support causes they care about in a way that is appealing, transparent, convenient, and financially sustainable. 

## Problem Statement

While most people view charitable giving as a meaningful way to support causes they are passionate about, there is a significant gap between intent and action. Although a majority of Americans have donated at least once, few maintain consistent giving habits even when they feel inclined to give. Often, people are deterred by a lack of convenience, financial insecurity, or a general mistrust of the donation process. These factors frequently prevent willing donors from following through with their support, even when they are intrinsically motivated to support the cause.

## User Research

To gain a deeper understanding of the disconnect between donor intent and action, we initiated our user research with a focus on user experiences and perspectives. Gauging potential interest in our project, we sought to conduct two rounds of user interviews with individuals with varying levels of experience donating to charities. 

### First Round

The first round of user interviews primarily focused on gaining general insight into a diverse breadth of donation experiences, revolving around a semi-structured interview method in which two group members interviewed each interviewee at a time, taking notes throughout the interview to notate each individual’s perspectives, opinions, and key ideas about their experiences. Following eighteen semi-structured interviews, we compiled notes about the overall sentiment individuals had about charitable donations. Among the insights collected, nearly all individuals interviewed in the first round had at least some experience donating to some extent, with the majority of donations being to charities. Others had donated to other causes, such as churches and nonprofits. Interviewees demonstrated some interest in donating, but did so inconsistently. 

### Revision of Methods

While our approach to the first round of user interviews was intentionally semi-structured to allow interviewees to elaborate on their perspectives in detail and to support our initial plan to understand a wide range of experiences, we realized that the level of depth in our interviews was insufficient to developing a strong problem statement and objective for our project. With the help of the CS 188 course staff in our Design Studio meeting, we were able to narrow down our objective for the project in order to focus in on key insights we as interviewers wanted to know from our interviewees. Thus, in preparation for the second round of user interviews, we revised our interview protocol to follow a strict structured interview format with a uniform set of questions, allowing us to probe deeper into the specific factors and pain points among users’ donation experiences. This targeted approach, focusing on the **why** (“Why do/don’t you donate?”) and **how** (“How do you donate”), was aimed to gain a stronger understanding of the perspectives associated with the lack of trust and inconvenience, respectively, that was often cited as causing reluctance amongst prospective donors. This focused approach allowed us to move beyond general sentiment and gather stronger evidence necessary to define our problem statement and ultimately devise our solution accordingly.

### Second Round

The second round of user interviews, with the emphasized focus on the why’s and how’s of users’ donation experiences, was conducted in a structured interview style. With these revisions, the goal was to gain a stronger sense of the root questions we sought to address and figure out why people don’t donate, despite believing that donating is an important way to support causes. Thirteen interviews were conducted following a uniform set of questions aimed to collect direct perspective and opinions from users, with allotted space for additional comments and insight following the prescribed questions as necessary. 

From the collected insights of thirteen interviewees, we were able to determine that the primary factors hindering them from being more engaged with donating. Interviewees cited a lack of trust with charitable donations, specifically a lack of confidence about whether or not the money they donated went directly to the stated intentions. Many interviewees mentioned recent scams or misuse of funds revolving charitable work, especially concerns about money not being used for the intended causes and charities facing no repercussions for wrongdoing. The ability to trust a charity, and a platform through which their money would be funneled through, was an important factor they considered. Additionally, being that the interviewee pool primarily consisted of fellow college students, an insufficient amount of financial freedom was often mentioned as another factor, given their pre-existing expenses such as food, rent, and tuition. As a result, a lack of disposable income forced many participants to view charitable giving as a luxury they could not currently justify, causing them to prioritize personal financial stability over supporting external causes despite their desire to help. 

### Analysis

From the insights we received following both rounds of user interviews, our user research determined that an effective solution would need to simultaneously establish credibility to address trust concerns revolving around charities, as well as lower the financial barrier to entry to accommodate users with limited financial flexibility.

## Design Goals

Our primary objective with Aspiration is to bridge the gap between intent and action surrounding the process of charitable donations. Through our user research, we identified that while users are intrinsically motivated to support causes they care about and give to charities, they often stop before donating due to friction associated with a lack of trust, inconvenience, and financial insecurity associated with traditional donation methods. Therefore, our overarching goal is to implement a solution that empowers users to support causes they care about by making charitable giving a seamless, transparent, and financially flexible process. 

### Evolution of Goal and Instructor Feedback

Initially, our design scope was overly broad in attempting to tackle issues regarding the general public’s “trust” in charitable giving to the non-profit sector. Complex questions such as how popularity correlates with trustworthiness, how to convey trust, and how to influence user perception of charities were discussed in Design Studio sessions with the course staff. The course staff instead advised us to pivot from trying to fix the *reputation* of charities to fixing the *interaction* of donating. Forcing users to trust a charity was not feasible as it could potentially be manipulative or perceived with wrong intentions. However, our project could instead focus on building a system that fosters trust through information visibility and operational convenience. Consequently we refined our focus for the project into three key ideas:

### Convenience

We aim to remove the active effort required to donate. By integrating Aspiration directly into online retail platforms by “rounding up” purchases to the nearest dollar and donating the difference, this makes donating a direct and convenient process and removes some of the friction involved with making donating an entirely separate task or major decision. This action is the core of one of our key interaction sequences. By implementing a “round-up” mechanism that integrates donation into existing purchasing activities, this transforms donating from a burdensome “task” into a more passive, convenient habit that can be combined with everyday transactions. 

### Trust

Acknowledging that we cannot control a charity’s off-platform reputation, our goal instead is to provide maximum clarity within our app to reassure users and convey a sense of trust through transparency. By ensuring the user interface clearly visualizes financial spending and trustworthiness of a charity using third-party charity verifications and impact reports through GiveWell, Aspiration can reduce some of the opacity that deters skeptical donors in a transparent and convenient manner. 

### Financial Flexibility and Control

Given that financial flexibility and control was an important consideration amongst the primary demographic of students and young professionals, we wanted to ensure that user control of their finances were not minimized while using Aspiration. Allowing users to both select the charity of their choosing to support and maintain full control of their donations was a key priority of this goal. Aspiration accomplishes this by allowing users to select the charity of their choice during the set-up process, with the option to change their charity at any time through an additional setting. 

## System Design and Implementation

Our system consists of a web app and a browser extension, where the web app is responsible for providing the user with relevant data that they may be interested in as well as creating an account, and the browser extension responsible for detecting online purchases to show a popup for donating the roundup amount. The web app would connect the user with their accounts to display relevant statistics and donation histories to inform them about their contributions. The browser extension allows them to easily make a donation in the form of a popup whenever they purchase something online. This way, they don’t have to manually go to websites or charities to donate, but rather incorporate consistent donations in their daily lives.

## Evaluation Methods and Analysis

In planning our evaluation, we initially hoped to measure whether our app could change users’ long-term donation behavior. After discussing feasibility with the TA, we narrowed our focus to questions that could realistically be examined within short, lab-style usability sessions. Our evaluation therefore closed in on two main questions: first, whether Aspiration actually makes donating feel simple and low-friction compared to the ways users usually donate; and second, whether the interface helps them feel informed and in control of where their money goes. These questions directly reflect the design goals that emerged from our earlier user research and design goals assignments, where convenience and transparency were identified as the most actionable levers for our team.

We conducted four individual usability sessions with UCLA students who resembled our target audience: college students with limited financial flexibility and mixed levels of prior experience with charitable giving. One of these sessions served as a pilot to refine our script and interaction flow, and the remaining three were treated as full study sessions. Each session lasted approximately twenty to thirty minutes and took place in person using a laptop running our web application and simulated browser extension. At the start of each session, we asked brief background questions about participants’ past donation habits, including whether they currently donate, how often they donate, and how much they trust online donation platforms. This contextual information helped us interpret later usability findings in light of participants’ prior experience.

The core of each session consisted of two end-to-end scenarios that were designed to exercise the central interaction sequences we had implemented. In the first scenario, the participant was asked to imagine they had just discovered Aspiration and wanted to try it for the first time. They created an account, selected at least one charity from a pre-defined list, and saw that everything was set up for them to begin using the app. In the second scenario, the participant was asked to visit an online shopping platform such as Amazon, and simulate a purchase by going to the checkout page. Once there, they will shortly be presented with a popup asking if they want to donate the roundup amount to the charity they had selected on the web app. After donating, they were prompted to return back to the web app to see their updated donation history and statistics. Throughout both scenarios, we used a think-aloud protocol and encouraged participants to verbalize what they were trying to do, what they expected to see next, and when they felt confused or uncertain.

To answer our evaluation questions, we collected both behavioral and self-reported data. During the tasks, we noted whether participants could complete each scenario without help, where they got stuck, and what kinds of errors or breakdowns occurred. We also paid attention to signs of friction such as long pauses, repeated backtracking, or attempts to look for information that was not visible on the current screen. After completing the interaction sequences, participants filled out a brief post-task questionnaire in which they rated, on a seven-point scale, how easy it was to understand the round-up flow, how comfortable they would feel using Aspiration with their own money, and how well they felt they understood where their donations were going. We then conducted a short semi-structured interview to probe more deeply into these ratings, asking participants to describe when they felt most or least confident, whether the system felt financially “safe” given their student budgets, and what they would want to change before adopting Aspiration in real life.

Our analysis followed the evaluation planning practices emphasized in the course. Given our small sample size, we treated the quantitative measures as descriptive indicators rather than as the basis for formal statistical tests. We summarized task outcomes and questionnaire responses to see whether there were consistent patterns in perceived ease of use and trust. We then reviewed our notes and, when necessary, the screen recordings to identify recurring interaction patterns and issues. Comments and observations were grouped into themes related to convenience, transparency, and control, and we examined how these themes mapped back to our original design goals. This mixed-method approach allowed us to connect what participants did in the interface with how they felt about the system and to derive grounded design implications for future iterations of Aspiration.

## Findings

Overall, our evaluation suggested that Aspiration’s core interaction of rounding up online purchases into micro-donations is understandable and generally appealing to our target users, but it also surfaced several pain points in the surrounding flows. Participants were consistently able to complete a round-up donation through the browser extension without major assistance, and several described the popup interaction as intuitive or comparable to other browser add-ons they had encountered. This indicates that the main mechanism of “see a popup at checkout and confirm a small extra charge” fits reasonably well into existing mental models for online payment and checkout experiences.

However, our observations showed that most friction occurred before and after this central moment. During first-time setup, participants frequently hesitated at the charity selection step. Some were unsure whether they were making a permanent commitment to a single organization and expressed a desire for more context, such as a short description or indication of impact, before deciding where their money would go. In one case, a participant attempted to skip charity selection entirely, expecting that they would be able to choose the recipient on a per-transaction basis instead. These behaviors suggested that participants did not always understand how flexible or reversible their choices were, even though the system technically supported changing settings later.

We also observed that participants responded positively to transparency features once they discovered them. On the dashboard, they appreciated seeing a clear donation history and cumulative total, and several commented that watching small round-ups add up over time made the concept feel more concrete and meaningful. At the same time, some transparency details were not immediately noticed. In the popup, the numerical breakdown of purchase amount, round-up amount, and total charge was sometimes overlooked because participants focused primarily on the main confirmation button. On the dashboard, information linking individual donations to specific charities was occasionally treated as secondary, leading a few participants to ask where exactly their money went despite the information being present in the interface.

Another recurring pattern concerned the balance between automation and control. Participants liked that Aspiration removed the need to navigate to separate charity websites or commit to large recurring donations, and several explicitly likened the experience to donating “spare change.” Yet, during the post-task conversations, almost every participant asked for additional ways to manage or limit their giving. Common requests included the ability to set a monthly cap on total round-up donations, to temporarily pause the feature during financially stressful periods, or to exclude certain merchants. These requests emerged even though participants were working with simulated money, which suggests that concerns about financial safety would likely be even stronger in real-world use.

Finally, across sessions, we noticed that perceptions of trust were sensitive to relatively small design details. Participants reported feeling more comfortable when labels were clear, branding was consistent, and confirmation messages explicitly stated what had just happened to their money. Conversely, ambiguous text, unfamiliar icons, or missing explanations led to questions about whether they would actually be willing to connect a real payment method to the system. Although Aspiration cannot directly address large-scale issues such as charity scandals or industry-wide mistrust, these observations indicate that small interface choices can either reinforce or undermine the limited trust that users are willing to extend to a new donation platform.

## Discussion

Our findings suggest that Aspiration is moving in a promising direction but still requires refinement before it can fully support sustainable donation habits. The evaluation confirmed that the basic round-up concept is compatible with students’ existing mental models of online shopping and that participants are receptive to turning “spare change” into charitable contributions. At the same time, the sessions highlighted how much work the surrounding flows need to do in order to make donating feel safe, understandable, and truly convenient for users who are financially constrained and already somewhat skeptical of online giving.

One key takeaway is that onboarding carries disproportionate weight for both convenience and trust. Our original implementation treated charity selection as a relatively straightforward setup step, but participants’ hesitation showed that this moment is actually a major psychological hurdle. Many of the concerns they brought up, such as not knowing how permanent their choice was or wanting more information about each organization, reflect deeper anxieties about misdirected funds and limited disposable income. In hindsight, we underestimated how strongly these concerns would surface at the very first decision point. A clearer explanation of how easily settings can be changed, combined with lightweight contextual information about each charity, could reduce this friction and make users feel more comfortable exploring the system in the first place.

A second takeaway is that transparency must be carefully integrated into key decision points rather than treated as an add-on feature. Our dashboard succeeded in making cumulative impact visible, but participants’ tendency to overlook the breakdown of amounts in the popup or the charity linkages in the history suggests that simply including information is not enough. Design-wise, this points us toward emphasizing the connection between each micro-donation and its recipient at the moment when the user is deciding whether to round up, not just afterward in a separate view. Future iterations could experiment with different layouts, typography, or microcopy to draw attention to this information without overwhelming the user, and potentially with small, scenario-appropriate impact cues (for example, how a given amount might be used) that retain our emphasis on transparency without slipping into manipulative persuasion.

Our evaluation also surfaced important limitations of the current prototype and study. First, our sample was small and restricted to UCLA students, which limits the generalizability of our results to other demographics such as working professionals or older donors. Second, the extension interactions were simulated in a study environment with fake purchases, which likely reduced the emotional and financial stakes of participants’ decisions. Users may behave differently when real bank accounts and actual budgets are involved. Third, the time frame of our study did not allow us to observe long-term effects, such as whether the novelty of round-up donations wears off or whether users become more trusting (or more suspicious) over time. These limitations mean that our conclusions are best understood as initial, directional insights rather than definitive evidence of behavior change.

Despite these constraints, the evaluation helped us identify concrete directions for future work. In the near term, we would prioritize redesigning the onboarding flow to better communicate flexibility, adding simple but visible controls such as monthly donation caps and pause toggles, and refactoring the popup to foreground the breakdown of amounts and the destination of funds. Longer term, we are interested in running longitudinal studies that integrate real or realistic payment data, which would allow us to track actual usage patterns, opt-out behaviors, and the evolution of trust over time. Another potential direction is to explore integrations with banks or payment providers to support in-person purchases, as we originally envisioned, while maintaining clear transparency about how data are used and how funds are routed.

The evaluation also revealed several mistakes and lessons learned in our design process. Early in the quarter, we framed our problem in terms of “solving” trust in charitable giving at a very broad level, which led us to spread our attention across too many issues at once. Only after discussions with course staff did we narrow our focus to the aspects of trust and convenience that we could actually influence through interface design. Similarly, in planning our evaluation, we initially aimed to measure shifts in long-term donation behavior, which was unrealistic given the time and resources available. The usability-focused study we ultimately conducted was more modest, but it produced actionable insights about micro-interactions and immediate perceptions that we could iterate on. These experiences underscored the importance of aligning research questions with what a given prototype and study design can meaningfully answer.

Finally, our evaluation raised new questions that we were not able to address within the scope of this project but that now shape how we think about systems like Aspiration. One question concerns how users’ donation behavior changes over time when round-ups are integrated into their daily routines: do they become desensitized and start ignoring the popup, or does seeing cumulative impact reinforce their motivation to continue? Another question is how different control mechanisms, such as monthly caps or budgeting tools, might affect both adoption and retention: would additional controls increase users’ willingness to sign up, or would they introduce complexity that undermines perceived convenience? We are also curious about how much transparency information is optimal at the moment of donation. There is a tension between providing enough detail to build trust and overwhelming users with information that slows them down. Exploring these questions would require more extensive, longitudinal, and possibly comparative studies, but they offer a roadmap for how Aspiration, and similar donation systems, could be studied and refined beyond this initial iteration.
